sql_command: SELECT COUNT(t.id) AS total_transactions FROM transactions t JOIN accounts a ON t.acc_id = a.id WHERE a.cus_id IN (SELECT d.cus_id FROM deposits d INTERSECT SELECT l.cus_id FROM loans l)

sql_command:

    SELECT DISTINCT c.id 
    FROM customers c
    JOIN accounts a ON c.id = a.cus_id

SELECT SUM(t.tran_amt) AS total_transaction_amount
FROM customers c
JOIN accounts a ON c.id = a.cus_id
JOIN (
  SELECT cus_id
  FROM accounts
  GROUP BY cus_id
  HAVING COUNT(DISTINCT acc_num) > 1
) multiple_accounts ON c.id = multiple_accounts.cus_id

sql_command:
SELECT COUNT(*) 
FROM deposits 
WHERE 
  (CASE 
    WHEN right(lower(tem), 1) = 'y' THEN CAST(left(tem, length(tem) - 1) AS INTEGER) * 12
    WHEN right(lower(tem), 1) = 'm' THEN CAST(left(tem, length(tem) - 1) AS INTEGER)
    ELSE 0
  END) 
  > 
  (
    SELECT AVG(
      CASE 
        WHEN right(lower(tem), 1) = 'y' THEN CAST(left(tem, length(tem) - 1) AS INTEGER) * 12
        WHEN right(lower(tem), 1) = 'm' THEN CAST(left(tem, length(tem) - 1) AS INTEGER)
        ELSE 0
      END
    )
    FROM deposits
  );
query: Count the number of deposits with term greater than average term.

sql_command: SELECT COUNT(*) FROM loans WHERE interest > (SELECT AVG(interest) FROM loans);

    SELECT brc, AVG(deposits.bal) AS avg_balance
    FROM deposits
    JOIN customers ON deposits.cus_id = customers.id

)

SELECT customers.brc, COUNT(*) AS deposit_count
FROM deposits
JOIN customers ON deposits.cus_id = customers.id
JOIN average_balances ON customers.brc = average_balances.brc

GROUP BY customers.brc
ORDER BY deposit_count DESC
LIMIT 5;
